Background

The main focus of this analysis is to study global trends in sustainable development. Sustainable development is essentially a way of measuring human development while taking into account ecological issues. The Sustainable Development Project, an academic research group, has created a Sustainable Development Index (SDI), which measures “the ecological efficiency of human development, recognizing that development must be achieved within planetary boundaries” (Sustainable Development Project 2015). More specifically, the SDI score divides a country’s human development index by its ecological impact index (which takes into account CO2 emissions and material footprint). With this SDI measurement, the higher a country’s index is, the better off that country is in terms of sustainable development.

Through this analysis, we hope to explore two main questions:

  1. How do countries’ development compare when incorporating the environment into the equation?
    • More specifically, how does SDI’s overall measurement differ from the individual variables regarding land use, renewables, and general energy usage?
    • Does SDI accurately predict a country’s renewable capability/ resource usage/ land use?
  2. How else can sustainable development be measured?
    • SDI and Land Use
    • SDI and Resource Usage
    • SDI and Resource Rent

Our data came from two primary sources: The Sustainable Development Index1 and The World Bank.2 Our year of analysis was 2015, as this was the most recent data available across all sources. Our data consists of the following categories as follows:

  • Sustainable Development Index (SDI)
    • Life Expectancy
    • Expected Years of Schooling
    • Mean Years of Schooling
    • Income (GNI per capita constant)
    • CO2 Emissions Per Capita
    • Material FOotprint per capita (tonnes)
  • Land Use
    • Agriculture (% of land area) by country
    • Forest: Forest area (% of land area) by country
    • Arable: Arable land (% of land area) by country
  • Energy and Renewable Resources
    • Access To Electricity (% of population)
    • Renewable Consumption (% of total energy consumption)
    • Total natural Resources Rent: (% of GDP by country)3

Data Analysis and Findings

We are analyzing our Data through three primary paradigms:

  • Univariate - Involving one variate or variable quantity
  • Bivariate - Explores the concept of relationship between two variables
  • Mapping - Exploring quantitative data by region/ globally

Univariate Analysis

Analysis of Sustainable Development


Main Findings: The first piece of analysis is a univariate plot of the existing Sustainable Development Index. Because there are so many countries to look at, we average the SDI score by continent. In general, the average SDI score is relatively similar across all continents–at around 0.6–although Europe has a slightly worse score, and South America’s score is a bit better. Considering the results of this plot, it may be important to note that looking at average SDI by continent essentially covers up the worst-performing countries’ scores. For example, the US, Canada, and Australia all have SDI scores under 0.2, but because other countries in North America and Oceania have quite high SDI scores, the continental averages are not brought down. With this in mind, it could be interesting for future studies to weigh SDI scores when computing regional averages like this–for example, by population–so that regions with poor-scoring impactful countries like the US, Canada, and Australia can be more accurately represented.

By calculating the differece between agricultural and arable land, we aim to see how much of the land that wasn’t meant for agriculture has been turned into agriculture and thus learning the average land development sustainability for each continent.

Main Findings:

Subset to only have the variables of Renewable consumption, SDI, Continent and Country for analysis：

SDI and Resource Rent


Main Findings: Another way to address our question of whether the SDI accurately measures sustainable development is by comparing SDI scores and resource rent. To clarify, resource rent essentially refers to how natural resources like oil, gas, forests, minerals, and coal contribute to a country’s GDP. Based on this plot, there not many discernible trends regarding the relationship between SDI score and resource rent. For the most part, however, the majority of countries and continents in general tend to have low resource rent values, while SDI score varies widely. This lack of a discernible relationship may indicate that including resource rent into the calculation of sustainable development could change the way that sustainable development is measured.


SDI and Renewable Energy Consumption


Main Findings: :There is a very weak connection between Renewable Energy Consumption and SDI. However, countries with the highest renewable consumption percentage(above 75%) are unlikely to have low SDI scores. 50-75% renewable consumption group, only Iceland and Norway Countries with very low renewable consumption. 0-50% renewable consumption group’s SDI scores scatter on the plot, ranging from the lowest to the highest. The lower percentage of renewable energy consumption is, the more varied the SDI scores are. For example, Algeria, nearly zero consumption of renewable energy consumption, is very sustainably developed in terms of SDI score.

It is interesting that Africa countries did very well in renewable usage in terms of consumption percentage. To the contrast, Europe, Asia, and North America did bad in renewable usage, while South America and Oceania’s points scatter among the scale. .

Main Findings: - Europe has high land development sustainability level and low SDI. - South America has low land development sustainability level and high SDI. - Africa has low land development sustainability level and relatively low SDI. - The continental comparison result is not consistent with the result in country level. We guess it’s partially due to our limitations in data processing. For example, when comparing continental average data, it’s better for us to calculate weighted mean instead of absolute mean, so that we can take into account more factors such as country size and GDP.

Original SDI Index

Main Findings: Note: Areas on the map with Grey indicate lack of data. This shows the existing SDI scoring system (higher is better). We chose to unify SDI scores by continent, as to make it clearer to differentiate. The Americas seem to score highly (particularly South America). while large parts of Asia (Russia and China) scoor not so well.

New SDI SDI Index

Main Findings: Note: Areas on the map with Grey indicate lack of data. Our new index includes these key variables: - Resource REnt - Forest: Forest area (% of land area) by country - Agriculture (% of land area) by country - Access To Electricity (% of population) - Arable: Arable land (% of land area) by country - Renewable Consumption (% of total energy consumption)

We chose these key variables, as we believe that these variables are the best indicators for our new index. Things have changed up quite a bit - For example, poor-performing countries under the original index–like Russia and China–are rated much better with our new index. Also, many countries in South America and Oceania that were highly-scoring have a worse performance with our new index.

Conclusion

In brief, adding in the six other variables changes how sustainable development is measured quite a bit. From the above discussion, we can come to the conclusion that the existing SDI scoring system doesn’t completely account for many measures of sustainability and human development. Our new index, therefore, might be a better indication of how countries around the world are really performing in terms of sustainable development. For future analysis, it would be interesting to conduct a weighted index per continent, where countries with larger population or size play a larger role in determining the “score” of the continent.
